00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:26.960
Professional translation work.

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:32.360
How many of you are full-time
professional translators?

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:35.260
And how many of you work in
translation, localization,

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:37.530
internationalization today?

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:38.450
OK.

00:02:38.450 --> 00:02:38.980
Great.

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:41.260
So, many of you are familiar
with some of the concepts that

00:02:41.260 --> 00:02:43.410
I'm gonna be talking about
today, and some of the stories

00:02:43.410 --> 00:02:44.290
that I'll be sharing.

00:02:44.290 --> 00:02:46.290
But I'm pretty sure there will
be other stories that you

00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:48.230
haven't heard yet that
come from the book.

00:02:48.230 --> 00:02:50.410
And hopefully, it will open up
your mind to how big this

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:52.490
field is, and how incredible
the field of

00:02:52.490 --> 00:02:54.710
translation really is.

00:02:54.710 --> 00:02:57.120
So, the first point that I
really want to make is that

00:02:57.120 --> 00:02:59.330
translation shapes our lives.

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:01.575
That's from the subtitle
of the book.

00:03:01.575 --> 00:03:04.250
And I don't just mean the people
who work in this field.

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:05.900
I mean everybody's life.

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:10.020
Translation affects every single
person in the world.

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:11.440
That's my premise.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:13.500
So, I'm going to give you some
stories that come from the

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:18.500
book that show exactly how
translation shapes our lives.

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:22.430
So, the first story is
about this word.

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:26.352
"Intoxicado." Now, how many
of you speak Spanish?

00:03:26.352 --> 00:03:27.940
A good number of people
speak Spanish.

00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:28.420
Excellent.

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:30.470
So I'm sure all of you know
how to translate this term

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:32.510
perfectly, right?

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:33.010
[LAUGHS]

00:03:33.010 --> 00:03:34.900
It's a tricky one.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:36.550
So, those of you who speak
Spanish, don't give me the

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:37.786
answer, please.

00:03:37.786 --> 00:03:39.410
[LAUGHS]

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:43.460
Those of you who don't speak
Spanish, looking at that word,

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:47.940
you probably think that it
means intoxicated, right?

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:50.690
So there was a bilingual
nurse in a Florida

00:03:50.690 --> 00:03:53.040
Hospital in the year 1980.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.120
And this bilingual nurse heard
the patient came in and his

00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:58.400
family said he was intoxicado.

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:01.960
So, how did he render that
word into English?

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:05.886
He said, he's intoxicated.

00:04:05.886 --> 00:04:08.410
There's just one problem.

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:10.690
It doesn't mean intoxicated.

00:04:10.690 --> 00:04:14.740
This is a pretty difficult word
to translate on its own.

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:17.130
I can give you some examples,
and you can help me figure out

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:18.190
the meaning.

00:04:18.190 --> 00:04:22.440
So "intoxicacion por plomo"
means lead poisoning.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:26.350
"Intoxicacion por alimentos,"
food poisoning.

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:29.590
"Intoxicacion solar,"
sun poisoning.

00:04:29.590 --> 00:04:32.230
So how do you translate the
word "intoxicado"--

00:04:32.230 --> 00:04:33.786
he's intoxicado?

00:04:33.786 --> 00:04:35.274
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:35.274 --> 00:04:35.770
NATALY KELLY: Yeah.

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:38.700
But do we say in English that
somebody's poisoned?

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:40.600
We really don't say
that, do we?

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:42.320
We say they have food
poisoning, or

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:43.930
they have sun poisoning.

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:46.930
So it just goes to show how
difficult it is to translate a

00:04:46.930 --> 00:04:48.850
single word like that.

00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:52.370
Now in this case, what happened
was that he was given

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:55.010
the wrong course of treatment
because of this mistranslated

00:04:55.010 --> 00:04:59.425
word, and a healthy young
man became quadriplegic.

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:07.180
Shortly after, a lawsuit
followed, and a $71 million

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:11.680
settlement was the result of
this mistranslation as well.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:17.220
So this is often known as
the $71 million word.

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:18.900
Right.

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:23.020
So there are consequences to
mistranslating a single term.

00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:25.980
Consequences that are important
in terms of the

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:28.950
human value, as well as the
economic and financial

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:30.960
repercussions.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:32.810
Let me give you another
example that also

00:05:32.810 --> 00:05:34.660
comes from the book.

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:38.830
So, this is an example of
something that happened in

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:41.150
Haiti, January 12, 2010.

00:05:41.150 --> 00:05:43.510
We remember what
happened then.

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:46.170
This was when the earthquake
took out most of the

00:05:46.170 --> 00:05:48.270
communications.

00:05:48.270 --> 00:05:49.930
Now, we have a special
guest with us today.

00:05:49.930 --> 00:05:53.660
Rob, would you mind
standing up?

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:59.580
So, Rob is a researcher, and
developed a very impressive

00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:05.720
system that was able to use the
only form of communication

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:07.860
that was available when
all other forms of

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:09.560
communication went down.

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:13.070
These were text messages
or SMS messages.

00:06:13.070 --> 00:06:15.390
So the system that
Rob created--

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:17.590
and his work as a researcher
at Stanford--

00:06:17.590 --> 00:06:20.840
was called Mission 4636.

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:24.670
And this system allowed him
to gather more than 1,000

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:27.380
volunteers in 49 countries.

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:29.840
And because of this system, in
the first six weeks after the

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:30.430
earthquake--

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:32.080
or after the program
was launched--

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:35.840
there were more than 40,000
messages that were translated

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:39.790
in 10 minutes or less,
all via text message.

00:06:39.790 --> 00:06:41.650
Now, you might think, well,
why would these

00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:43.870
text messages matter?

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:46.730
The rescuers who were rescuing
people on the ground spoke

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:47.470
different languages.

00:06:47.470 --> 00:06:49.760
Many of them were coming through
international aid and

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:51.290
relief organizations.

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:53.540
So in order for them to reach
people-- in order for them to

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.450
find out what was wrong, give
them lifesaving treatment,

00:06:56.450 --> 00:06:58.960
help them find shelter, help
them find safety--

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:01.740
those translations
really mattered.

00:07:01.740 --> 00:07:02.870
They saved human lives.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:05.310
They saved hundreds of lives.

00:07:05.310 --> 00:07:08.240
So the work that Rob did, and
the work that all those

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:10.400
volunteer translators did,
had a tremendous

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:13.710
impact on human life.

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:16.330
But if you're not convinced yet
that translation shapes

00:07:16.330 --> 00:07:19.180
your life, I'll give you
another example.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:21.850
Because, so far, I've shown you
how translation affects

00:07:21.850 --> 00:07:23.220
other people's lives.

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:25.290
So you might be asking, well,
how does it affect me?

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:26.030
Tell me about me.

00:07:26.030 --> 00:07:28.410
I care about me.

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:30.090
So here's an example for you.

00:07:30.090 --> 00:07:32.250
The Global Public Health
Intelligence Network, also

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:35.300
known as GPHIN, is mining--

00:07:35.300 --> 00:07:36.200
constantly--

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:39.670
global news reports, and using
automatic translation

00:07:39.670 --> 00:07:42.030
technology to translate
articles

00:07:42.030 --> 00:07:44.460
from English and into--

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:46.220
into and out of English and
eight other languages.

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:48.150
So this is machine translation,
automatic

00:07:48.150 --> 00:07:50.030
translation.

00:07:50.030 --> 00:07:53.840
Now, what you might not know
about this system is that

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:55.850
Swine Flu and SARS--

00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:57.030
the first cases--

00:07:57.030 --> 00:08:00.560
were detected by this
particular system.

00:08:00.560 --> 00:08:02.660
What it's doing is scanning
for important

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:04.210
key words, for symptoms.

00:08:04.210 --> 00:08:05.560
For things like fever.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:06.740
For things like sneezing.

00:08:06.740 --> 00:08:09.270
For some of these symptoms that
are the first indicators

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:12.140
of a public health outbreak.

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:15.950
So the system issued alerts in
those cases, and the response

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:18.910
and containment efforts
followed.

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:21.820
So this goes you to show that
translation is behind the

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:24.630
scenes, keeping us safe,
preventing public health

00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:25.880
outbreaks from spreading.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:30.350
How else does translation
shape our lives?

00:08:30.350 --> 00:08:32.620
If you're not convinced yet,
I'll give you another

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:35.159
compelling example.

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:37.360
On September 10, 2001--

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:40.539
the day before the
9/11 attacks--

00:08:40.539 --> 00:08:43.559
there were some warnings
that were caught.

00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:45.710
Warnings that were
issued about what

00:08:45.710 --> 00:08:46.810
was about to happen.

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:50.530
So the words "tomorrow is zero
hour" and the words "the match

00:08:50.530 --> 00:08:53.970
is about to begin"
were intercepted.

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:57.810
These were recorded and
intercepted from al-Qaeda

00:08:57.810 --> 00:09:00.872
operatives by US intelligence
agencies.

00:09:00.872 --> 00:09:04.610
Now, there was just
one problem.

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:07.730
These messages were
not in English.

00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:10.230
They were in Arabic.

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:11.516
So when do you think they
were translated?

00:09:15.210 --> 00:09:19.486
September 12, 2001.

00:09:19.486 --> 00:09:23.150
And it's not to say that if
these had been translated on

00:09:23.150 --> 00:09:25.580
the day that they were
intercepted, that the 9/11

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:27.340
attacks would have necessarily
been prevented.

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:30.150
Obviously, a lot has to happen
for something to be considered

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:32.540
a credible threat, and
a lot of wheels have

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:34.670
to be put in motion.

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:37.330
But it does go to show the
importance of not only

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:40.560
translation, but translation
that happens quickly.

00:09:40.560 --> 00:09:43.680
Translation that can happen
efficiently, systematically.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:47.030
So this comes from official
US Government documents.

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:49.270
Anyone can look up
this information.

00:09:49.270 --> 00:09:52.440
And it's a well-known fact that
the US Government has had

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:55.470
a backlog-- tremendous backlog--
of translation that

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.470
hasn't been carried out.

00:09:57.470 --> 00:09:59.660
And this is a constant
struggle that the US

00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:00.940
Government officials
are still facing.

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:06.990
So, what happens when
countries go to war?

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:09.690
How does translation
play a role then?

00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:12.230
Well, translators and
interpreters are constantly

00:10:12.230 --> 00:10:16.810
being used when countries come
into conflict with each other.

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:21.540
This is a picture of a man who
everybody needs to know.

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:24.220
Everybody watching needs to
know and remember the

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:24.910
name of this man.

00:10:24.910 --> 00:10:27.480
He is one of the true heroes
of the interpreting

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:28.660
profession.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:31.450
His name is Peter Less.

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:34.630
Now, Peter Less was an
interpreter at the Nuremberg

00:10:34.630 --> 00:10:39.620
Trials, where the Nazi war
criminals were tried.

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:44.430
Peter had the difficult task
of rendering testimony, and

00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:46.340
rendering the words
of some of the

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:49.430
masterminds of the Holocaust.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:52.720
This was even more difficult, in
his case, because he was a

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:55.160
Holocaust survivor himself.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:56.910
In fact, his entire family--

00:10:56.910 --> 00:10:59.370
his parents, his siblings,
his grandmother--

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:02.100
were killed in Auschwitz.

00:11:02.100 --> 00:11:05.240
So he had to be the voice
of the people who were

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:08.560
responsible for these
atrocities.

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:11.970
Can you imagine how difficult
that must have been?

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:15.860
But yet, he was able to stand
to that task and to carry it

00:11:15.860 --> 00:11:18.490
out heroically.

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:21.410
So he is a name who I hope we
will always think of when we

00:11:21.410 --> 00:11:25.320
think of why translation
matters in the world.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:28.240
And again, you may say, this
doesn't affect me.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:30.250
This is all about
other people.

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:32.690
But when we think about access
to justice, and we think about

00:11:32.690 --> 00:11:37.580
carrying out the proceedings
in the legal system,

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:40.490
translation truly does
affect all of us.

00:11:40.490 --> 00:11:44.810
If any of us is a victim of a
crime, and the only witness

00:11:44.810 --> 00:11:47.650
speaks a language other than
English, do we want to deny

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:50.130
them an interpreter?

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:51.160
Absolutely not.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:55.480
Even the most pro-English-only
person would want that person

00:11:55.480 --> 00:11:57.170
to be able to state
what happened

00:11:57.170 --> 00:11:59.090
if they were a victim.

00:11:59.090 --> 00:12:01.000
So I think it highlights
the importance of

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.860
translation in our world.

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:04.700
But I'm not done.

00:12:04.700 --> 00:12:07.520
I'll give you another example.

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:10.610
This is another woman who I
would love you to know.

00:12:10.610 --> 00:12:14.900
Her name is Mara Clara Sharupi
Jua, and she is from the Shuar

00:12:14.900 --> 00:12:19.350
indigenous group in the
Ecuadorian Amazon.

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.290
And she is a poet.

00:12:21.290 --> 00:12:24.750
And she's here in this picture
reading some of her poems.

00:12:24.750 --> 00:12:27.650
And she writes poems in
Shuar and in Spanish.

00:12:27.650 --> 00:12:31.500
And I'm very privileged to be
her translator, to translate

00:12:31.500 --> 00:12:33.330
her poetry into English.

00:12:33.330 --> 00:12:37.320
Now, you may think, why should
I care, Nataly, about a

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:41.060
translator of a language that
is in the Ecuadorian Amazon?

00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:43.790
How does this affect me?

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:46.410
Well, it does affect you.

00:12:46.410 --> 00:12:49.460
Because one in every four
ingredients in pharmaceutical

00:12:49.460 --> 00:12:54.100
products come from the
Amazon rainforest.

00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:58.190
And only between 10 and 20% of
the plants in the Amazon

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:01.090
rainforest have been
categorized.

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:06.310
So, many of the secrets of
healing and powers of curing

00:13:06.310 --> 00:13:10.300
diseases are locked up in
languages like the one that

00:13:10.300 --> 00:13:11.970
she speaks.

00:13:11.970 --> 00:13:15.140
So, if there is a cure for
AIDS, for cancer, for

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:18.220
diabetes, for a lot of
the ails of society--

00:13:18.220 --> 00:13:19.380
ailments--

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:22.140
chances are they're there
in the Amazon.

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:25.220
And they're locked up in
languages that translation has

00:13:25.220 --> 00:13:26.470
the power to unlock.

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:31.470
So hopefully I've convinced
you now that translation

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:33.320
affects your lives.

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:35.720
Now I'd like to try to convince
you that translation

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:38.440
can be found pretty
much everywhere.

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:42.150
And this is where things
start to get exciting.

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:44.730
So, right now, there is actually
a conference going on

00:13:44.730 --> 00:13:48.020
in San Diego at the American
Translators Association.

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:49.820
And the American Translators
Association has

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:51.230
about 11,000 members.

00:13:51.230 --> 00:13:53.640
There are about 2,000
people there.

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:56.310
And I just was looking on their
conference website at

00:13:56.310 --> 00:13:59.480
some of the sessions that
are happening right now.

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:03.460
So we have sessions going on
right now that deal with

00:14:03.460 --> 00:14:06.870
German accounting standards,
patent abstract translation in

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:10.790
French, interpreting proverbs
and idioms in Korean.

00:14:10.790 --> 00:14:12.900
Criminal Terminology
in Brazil.

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:14.930
Slang and Taboo for
the Courts.

00:14:14.930 --> 00:14:17.150
Translating and Interpreting
War Crimes Trials for

00:14:17.150 --> 00:14:20.010
Bosnian/Serbian/Croatian.

00:14:20.010 --> 00:14:23.820
Translating Sexist and
Gender-Neutral Language.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:26.510
Things like understanding the
clinical trials that you're

00:14:26.510 --> 00:14:28.270
translating and the
science behind it.

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:30.130
Subtitling Motion Pictures.

00:14:30.130 --> 00:14:34.010
Translating for Design and
Construction in Israel.

00:14:34.010 --> 00:14:37.440
Advancing Productivity Using
Voice Recognition.

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:40.550
And one of my personal
favorites, Building Your Own

00:14:40.550 --> 00:14:43.950
Statistical Machine Translation
Systems.

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:47.770
Very interesting that there is
a session that is to teach

00:14:47.770 --> 00:14:51.260
translators how to build
their own systems.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:53.580
So you can see that translation
is in all kinds of

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:54.650
different places.

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:57.820
And in the book, we talk about
translation of Harlequin

00:14:57.820 --> 00:14:58.830
romance novels--

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:00.770
something light-hearted--

00:15:00.770 --> 00:15:04.710
but translation also of holy
books and sacred texts, which

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:05.890
isn't so light-hearted.

00:15:05.890 --> 00:15:08.510
A much more serious topic.

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:11.560
Translators and interpreters
are used in outer space by

00:15:11.560 --> 00:15:14.710
astronauts to communicate with
engineers on the ground who

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:17.360
speak other languages.

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:17.970
And--

00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:20.840
on another lighthearted note--
if you go to the opera, you

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:23.755
might be handled a libretto that
has been translated so

00:15:23.755 --> 00:15:26.490
that you can understand
what it says.

00:15:26.490 --> 00:15:29.560
Translators are out there
helping come up with exact

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:31.950
wording for peace treaties,
so that both sides

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:33.770
will agree to them.

00:15:33.770 --> 00:15:37.770
And they're also translating
video games.

00:15:37.770 --> 00:15:40.820
And translators are also
enabling us to use social

00:15:40.820 --> 00:15:44.720
media platforms, which can be
used for fun, and also for

00:15:44.720 --> 00:15:46.270
more serious things.

00:15:46.270 --> 00:15:49.150
Like revolutions, enabling
people to connect, enabling

00:15:49.150 --> 00:15:53.330
people to communicate
and organize.

00:15:53.330 --> 00:15:56.310
So, my next important point that
we make throughout the

00:15:56.310 --> 00:16:01.690
book is that translation
isn't easy.

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:04.650
Everybody here who has done that
can probably attest to

00:16:04.650 --> 00:16:07.850
the fact that that's true.

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:11.520
So, a lot of people who are
working in this field have

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:12.230
this question.

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:15.243
Well, if I'm bilingual, can
I become a translator?

00:16:15.243 --> 00:16:16.170
[LAUGHS]

00:16:16.170 --> 00:16:18.650
We've all been asked
that, right?

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:21.790
But the best way to answer that
question, I think, is

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:23.570
that not everybody who knows
how to write can be a

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:25.360
professional writer.

00:16:25.360 --> 00:16:27.400
Just because you cook dinner
every night doesn't make you a

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:28.930
professional chef.

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:30.240
Just because you drive
a car doesn't

00:16:30.240 --> 00:16:32.680
make you Mario Andretti.

00:16:32.680 --> 00:16:34.760
The same thing is true
for translators.

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:36.970
Just because you know two
languages does not make you a

00:16:36.970 --> 00:16:39.670
professional translator.

00:16:39.670 --> 00:16:42.010
And the proof that we also
have to offer people that

00:16:42.010 --> 00:16:46.480
translation isn't so easy
is that when people take

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:49.500
professional translation exams,
the passing rates are

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:52.110
usually very low--

00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:55.700
around 20% for most exams for
translators and interpreters.

00:16:55.700 --> 00:16:59.000
So of 8 out of 10 bilingual
individuals who are failing

00:16:59.000 --> 00:16:59.470
these tests.

00:16:59.470 --> 00:17:01.590
That goes to show that it takes
more than just fluency

00:17:01.590 --> 00:17:03.960
in two languages to
be a translator.

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:05.700
The reason for that is
because, of course,

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:07.550
words can be tricky.

00:17:07.550 --> 00:17:08.640
They can be misunderstood.

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:09.660
They can be misconstrued.

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:12.050
They can be taken
out of context.

00:17:12.050 --> 00:17:15.050
And that's just in
one language.

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:16.790
All we have to do is just
think of the classic

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:19.380
"telephone" game, where one
person whispers to the next,

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:20.349
to the next, to the next.

00:17:20.349 --> 00:17:21.920
And by the end of it, we get a

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:24.130
completely transformed message.

00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:25.380
And that's just in
one language.

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:31.190
Language also never
stops evolving.

00:17:31.190 --> 00:17:34.800
It is completely unique
to each person.

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:37.550
My husband sent out an email
blast to a bunch of people to

00:17:37.550 --> 00:17:39.130
let them know about the book.

00:17:39.130 --> 00:17:41.360
And he wrote, apologies
for the spousal spam.

00:17:43.910 --> 00:17:45.520
And I thought, oh, a new term.

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:47.000
OK, where did he get this?

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:48.970
So I asked him, where
did you hear that?

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:51.690
And he said, oh, I
just made it up.

00:17:51.690 --> 00:17:54.240
That's just one example
of human creativity.

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:55.820
We come up with new terms
all the time.

00:17:55.820 --> 00:17:58.400
We coin new terms
all the time.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:03.670
And that's why humans are so
necessary for translation.

00:18:03.670 --> 00:18:04.920
But when we think about
spoken language,

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:05.880
it's much more complex.

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:08.280
Obviously we have things like
tone of voice to worry about.

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:10.340
We have accent and
pronunciation.

00:18:10.340 --> 00:18:12.750
We even have things like
volume levels.

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:16.450
And, of course, translation of
spoken language interpretation

00:18:16.450 --> 00:18:18.590
is affected by other things that
aren't necessarily within

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:19.790
our control.

00:18:19.790 --> 00:18:21.620
So we have the equipment
that we're using.

00:18:21.620 --> 00:18:24.540
We have less predictable things
like background noise,

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:25.830
interference.

00:18:25.830 --> 00:18:27.710
Even if someone has a sore
throat, that can affect our

00:18:27.710 --> 00:18:29.700
ability to comprehend them.

00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:31.940
So there's all these other
variables that can interfere

00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:35.300
with an interpreter's ability
to render information

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:37.000
accurately.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.540
So when we start to talk about
more than one language--

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:42.430
we say in the book that
languages are like different

00:18:42.430 --> 00:18:43.810
instruments.

00:18:43.810 --> 00:18:44.790
They have different scales.

00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:46.440
They have different sounds.

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:49.340
Sometimes they don't even
have the same notes.

00:18:49.340 --> 00:18:52.590
You can't physically play the
same note in the same range or

00:18:52.590 --> 00:18:54.535
the same octave on
one instrument

00:18:54.535 --> 00:18:56.580
as you can on another.

00:18:56.580 --> 00:18:59.310
So we actually wrote in the book
that poetry translation

00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:02.426
is like playing a piano
sonata on a trombone.

00:19:02.426 --> 00:19:04.460
And I really think that's true,
because I'm currently

00:19:04.460 --> 00:19:06.770
trying to translate some poetry
that was originally

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:07.640
written in Shuar.

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:10.380
And to get that to come
into English is a

00:19:10.380 --> 00:19:13.150
pretty mighty challenge.

00:19:13.150 --> 00:19:16.490
I would also say it's not just
poetry translation that

00:19:16.490 --> 00:19:18.480
presents this problem.

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:21.740
How many of you saw in the
recent debates the Romney

00:19:21.740 --> 00:19:24.430
quote that's been everywhere--
binders full of women.

00:19:24.430 --> 00:19:25.930
[LAUGHTER].

00:19:25.930 --> 00:19:26.230
NATALY KELLY: OK.

00:19:26.230 --> 00:19:27.767
How do you translate that?

00:19:27.767 --> 00:19:29.020
[LAUGHS]

00:19:29.020 --> 00:19:30.410
It's not so easy to translate.

00:19:30.410 --> 00:19:32.750
So I wonder how this was
translated in the news for

00:19:32.750 --> 00:19:34.330
international media.

00:19:34.330 --> 00:19:36.600
But to make it even more
complicated, after this all

00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:39.060
came out, I saw an
image that was

00:19:39.060 --> 00:19:41.000
shared, and it had Beyonce.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.300
And it said, if you like it,
then you better put three

00:19:43.300 --> 00:19:45.540
rings on it.

00:19:45.540 --> 00:19:48.380
And it was referring to
a three-ring binder.

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:51.420
And I thought, this is a
translator's nightmare.

00:19:51.420 --> 00:19:53.450
Because not only do you have
to know something about

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:56.140
Beyonce, you have to know
something about current events

00:19:56.140 --> 00:19:57.720
in American politics.

00:19:57.720 --> 00:20:00.430
You have to know about gender
relations and these things

00:20:00.430 --> 00:20:03.500
that are happening in the news
with regard to women and

00:20:03.500 --> 00:20:04.640
women's rights.

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:07.450
And you have to know that, in
the United States, people use

00:20:07.450 --> 00:20:10.440
three-ring binders, which aren't
necessarily used in

00:20:10.440 --> 00:20:11.030
every country.

00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:13.030
Other countries have two-ring
binders, or four-ring binders,

00:20:13.030 --> 00:20:14.450
or six-ring binders.

00:20:14.450 --> 00:20:17.910
So it's very complicated to try
to migrate that concept

00:20:17.910 --> 00:20:22.540
and that humor, especially
into another language.

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:24.160
Terminology knowledge is
another reason that

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:26.210
translation is difficult.

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:30.030
The average person uses about
4,000 to 5,000 words in

00:20:30.030 --> 00:20:33.820
English on a regular basis.

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:35.400
People who are educated--

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:37.420
who've received a basic
education--

00:20:37.420 --> 00:20:40.380
between 8,000 and
10,000 words.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:43.400
The professions that use the
widest vocabularies use more

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:45.815
than double that amount
of words.

00:20:45.815 --> 00:20:50.300
So how many words you think
translators have to know?

00:20:50.300 --> 00:20:53.560
Well, many of them are crossing
many disciplines, and

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:57.320
many are going into more than
one language, so they are

00:20:57.320 --> 00:20:59.520
obviously have to know this kind
of vocabulary in at least

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:00.770
two languages.

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:05.070
So to give you another example
of why translation is so

00:21:05.070 --> 00:21:09.080
difficult, I thought I
would show you this.

00:21:09.080 --> 00:21:10.970
So, numbers don't need
translation, right?

00:21:10.970 --> 00:21:12.420
You can just transfer
them across

00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:14.690
languages with no problem.

00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:16.044
Right?

00:21:16.044 --> 00:21:16.968
[LAUGHS]

00:21:16.968 --> 00:21:19.870
Does anyone know what these
numbers have in common, aside

00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:22.360
from the fact that they're
on signs, these images?

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:26.970
How about if I show you this?

00:21:30.578 --> 00:21:34.710
Does anyone want to volunteer to
take Flight 666 and sit in

00:21:34.710 --> 00:21:37.840
seat number 13?

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:40.580
These are bad luck numbers
in this culture, right?

00:21:40.580 --> 00:21:42.560
But they might not be bad luck
numbers in every culture.

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:47.140
And all the numbers up here are
bad luck in some culture.

00:21:47.140 --> 00:21:50.060
So you can't just transfer
these numbers when you're

00:21:50.060 --> 00:21:53.100
translating a marketing
campaign, an advertising

00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:57.350
campaign, or maybe even
a flight number.

00:21:57.350 --> 00:22:00.110
To give you another example of
how difficult translation can

00:22:00.110 --> 00:22:03.030
be, I thought I would tell you
this little story about

00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:05.010
President Carter.

00:22:05.010 --> 00:22:07.390
So President Carter, when
he was in office, became

00:22:07.390 --> 00:22:08.990
accustomed to working
with interpreters.

00:22:08.990 --> 00:22:13.300
And after he left office, he
went to Japan, and he was

00:22:13.300 --> 00:22:15.400
giving a talk at a school.

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:17.410
And since he had worked with
interpreters many times

00:22:17.410 --> 00:22:19.660
throughout his career, he
thought, OK, I'm gonna use a

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:22.400
joke, but I know it's really
hard to interpret jokes.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:23.830
So I'm gonna make it short.

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:27.020
I'm gonna keep it as a pretty
easy, short joke.

00:22:27.020 --> 00:22:32.820
So he told this joke, and the
audience erupted in laughter

00:22:32.820 --> 00:22:34.740
after the interpreter rendered
it into Japanese.

00:22:34.740 --> 00:22:36.363
They just died laughing.

00:22:36.363 --> 00:22:37.330
And he thought, wow.

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:38.350
This is the best response.

00:22:38.350 --> 00:22:40.400
I've ever had to a joke.

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:42.920
I wonder what the interpreter's
secret is?

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.120
So he went up to the interpreter
and asked-- and at

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:47.590
first she didn't want to say.

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:51.470
But then, he asked again, and
the interpreter said, "Mr.

00:22:51.470 --> 00:22:54.250
President, I told the audience,
President Carter

00:22:54.250 --> 00:22:55.490
told a funny story.

00:22:55.490 --> 00:22:56.700
Everyone must laugh."

00:22:56.700 --> 00:22:57.950
[LAUGHTER].

00:23:07.200 --> 00:23:10.360
Made the interpreter's
life easier.

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:12.810
It isn't easy to translate
humor, even if you're a

00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:14.910
professional interpreter.

00:23:14.910 --> 00:23:16.620
So you can see how hard
translation and

00:23:16.620 --> 00:23:19.130
interpreting can be.

00:23:19.130 --> 00:23:22.900
Now I'd like to talk a little
bit about the future.

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:24.640
I believe that translation
is going to lead

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:28.550
us into a new era.

00:23:28.550 --> 00:23:30.340
What do I mean by that?

00:23:30.340 --> 00:23:34.210
So I started to look in history
for other professions

00:23:34.210 --> 00:23:37.000
that have made a dramatic
impact on the world.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:38.620
And one of the professions
that came up

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:41.010
was this guy here.

00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:42.850
Blacksmiths.

00:23:42.850 --> 00:23:47.380
So, in a certain time period,
blacksmiths were seen kind of

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:48.410
like magicians.

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:49.540
They could do magical things.

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:51.280
They could transform metal--

00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:54.230
a hard surface-- and soften
it, and make it look

00:23:54.230 --> 00:23:57.110
beautiful, and do really
important things with it.

00:23:57.110 --> 00:23:59.190
In fact, many people in villages
would come to them,

00:23:59.190 --> 00:24:01.050
and they were doing all
kinds of things.

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:04.075
Not only creating every
single nail--

00:24:04.075 --> 00:24:05.710
I mean, it's hard to imagine
we couldn't just go

00:24:05.710 --> 00:24:06.670
buy a box of nails.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:08.320
Each one had to be
hand crafted.

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:10.780
But they were doing things
like dental work, and

00:24:10.780 --> 00:24:13.030
veterinary work, and all
kinds of things.

00:24:13.030 --> 00:24:15.000
Even warming the bread
and baking the

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:16.010
bread for the villages.

00:24:16.010 --> 00:24:18.030
Because they were some of the
few people who knew how to

00:24:18.030 --> 00:24:20.680
keep fires going.

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:23.540
So, blacksmiths played a
very important role.

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:25.440
And they're-- much like
translators, their work

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:27.330
touched all different
aspects of society.

00:24:30.440 --> 00:24:32.900
They were actually the lynchpin
of progress for the

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:35.770
Industrial Revolution.

00:24:35.770 --> 00:24:38.640
As needs became more complex,
so did the skills that were

00:24:38.640 --> 00:24:40.970
needed by blacksmiths.

00:24:40.970 --> 00:24:44.170
And they were actually involved
in helping build the

00:24:44.170 --> 00:24:48.970
machines that would eventually
replace their role.

00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:51.710
And they gave rise to a new way
of life, a new economy, a

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:52.290
new society.

00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:55.750
A whole new way of life.

00:24:55.750 --> 00:24:58.360
And that role actually evolved
into many other professions

00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:01.020
that did not exist previously
in history.

00:25:01.020 --> 00:25:03.910
So, things like welders,
machinists, pipefitters.

00:25:03.910 --> 00:25:06.570
And there were also a lot of
blacksmiths that went on to

00:25:06.570 --> 00:25:08.800
invent great things using
their skills and their

00:25:08.800 --> 00:25:12.830
knowledge, like Studebaker,
John Deere, Henry Ford.

00:25:12.830 --> 00:25:14.080
These were all blacksmiths.

00:25:16.380 --> 00:25:18.890
So even after their role was
transformed, they continued to

00:25:18.890 --> 00:25:22.710
make major contributions.

00:25:22.710 --> 00:25:23.580
So, I want to talk--

00:25:23.580 --> 00:25:25.920
I'm gonna come back to the
idea of blacksmiths and

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:28.710
translators and what they
have in common.

00:25:28.710 --> 00:25:31.270
But the question that you're
probably asking is-- because

00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:33.130
blacksmiths kind
of faded away--

00:25:33.130 --> 00:25:36.520
does that mean translators are
also going to fade away?

00:25:36.520 --> 00:25:39.670
Well, here's where I think
there's a difference between

00:25:39.670 --> 00:25:43.130
what blacksmiths did and what
translators are doing.

00:25:43.130 --> 00:25:44.560
So the big question is--
that everybody

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:45.910
asks me all the time--

00:25:45.910 --> 00:25:47.753
is will human translators
be replaced?

00:25:50.330 --> 00:25:53.220
I think when you compare them
to blacksmiths, you can ask

00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:56.120
people to use identical nails,
you can standardize things

00:25:56.120 --> 00:25:58.220
like railroad ties.

00:25:58.220 --> 00:26:00.820
But can you ask people to
use identical words?

00:26:00.820 --> 00:26:03.020
Can you ask everybody to
speak the same way?

00:26:03.020 --> 00:26:05.660
Can you ask people to mass
produce content?

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:08.190
Can it be like a factory
assembly line?

00:26:08.190 --> 00:26:11.570
How much content can
be mass produced?

00:26:11.570 --> 00:26:14.820
And how much has to
be customized?

00:26:14.820 --> 00:26:18.560
So, let's take a look at what
some of the data says.

00:26:18.560 --> 00:26:20.630
So, some of the stats I'm gonna
show you here come from

00:26:20.630 --> 00:26:22.740
Common Sense Advisory.

00:26:22.740 --> 00:26:25.200
So, the market today
is worth more than

00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:27.500
$33 billion US dollars--

00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:29.950
the market for language services
and technology.

00:26:29.950 --> 00:26:32.220
That's as of 2012.

00:26:32.220 --> 00:26:36.560
And the market is growing
at a rate of 12.17%.

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:40.050
Now, the market has continued
to grow steadily throughout

00:26:40.050 --> 00:26:41.530
the recession.

00:26:41.530 --> 00:26:44.220
Unlike many industries, this
market has continued to grow.

00:26:44.220 --> 00:26:46.580
Now, the growth did slow down
a bit during the global

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:47.660
economic downturn.

00:26:47.660 --> 00:26:51.160
But it continued to grow, and
historically has always grown

00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:54.810
yearly in double-digit
growth rates.

00:26:54.810 --> 00:26:58.260
There are more than 26,000
translation agencies or

00:26:58.260 --> 00:27:02.270
companies offering translation
services throughout the world.

00:27:02.270 --> 00:27:04.400
And our estimates tend to be
pretty conservative compared

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:06.250
to some of the other government
estimates

00:27:06.250 --> 00:27:08.800
that are out there.

00:27:08.800 --> 00:27:13.170
So, North America is not the
only important area of the

00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:14.590
world when it comes
to translation.

00:27:14.590 --> 00:27:16.160
In fact, it's not even
the biggest.

00:27:16.160 --> 00:27:20.200
Europe is quite a bit larger,
and North America makes up

00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:21.560
less than a third.

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:24.420
But translation is a global
industry, as you can see here.

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:26.450
And the dynamics and the
distribution of how this

00:27:26.450 --> 00:27:29.900
market is changing are different
every single year

00:27:29.900 --> 00:27:30.510
that we look at it.

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:31.720
Asia is rising.

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:33.140
We're seeing North America
play less of a

00:27:33.140 --> 00:27:34.630
role than in the past.

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:37.120
So, these things are changing
year by year.

00:27:39.660 --> 00:27:42.780
But this market is made up of
many, many services, not just

00:27:42.780 --> 00:27:43.350
translation.

00:27:43.350 --> 00:27:45.170
Obviously, software
localization--

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:47.000
which a lot of you are
interested in--

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.880
on-site interpreting, website
globalization, multimedia

00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:50.570
localization--

00:27:50.570 --> 00:27:54.110
all of these are encompassed
within this broader market.

00:27:54.110 --> 00:27:57.310
But translation is by far the
biggest service, because it's

00:27:57.310 --> 00:28:00.060
used by pretty much every type
of organization that

00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:02.760
you can think of.

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:06.110
Demand for translation
is growing.

00:28:06.110 --> 00:28:09.360
We did a study of Fortune 500
companies, and the vast

00:28:09.360 --> 00:28:12.090
majority told us that their
translation volumes have

00:28:12.090 --> 00:28:13.420
increased, and that
they expect them

00:28:13.420 --> 00:28:14.800
to continue to increase.

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:16.600
Their content volumes
were increasing at

00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:19.110
an even faster pace.

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:22.990
So the potential demand for
translation is enormous.

00:28:22.990 --> 00:28:26.240
Some studies show that there are
2.5 quintillion bytes of

00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:27.370
data-- of information--

00:28:27.370 --> 00:28:30.490
coming into existence
every single day.

00:28:30.490 --> 00:28:34.820
Translation providers are
converting a tiny, tiny

00:28:34.820 --> 00:28:35.520
fraction of that--

00:28:35.520 --> 00:28:39.850
0.00000067%.

00:28:39.850 --> 00:28:42.640
That's how much they are
converting every day.

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:45.770
So, if even just a tiny fraction
of that information

00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:49.840
is useful for translation
purposes, that signifies

00:28:49.840 --> 00:28:53.280
enormous potential
for translation.

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:55.460
What a lot of people don't
realize, when they talk about

00:28:55.460 --> 00:28:59.430
machine translation replacing
humans, is that human

00:28:59.430 --> 00:29:01.870
translators already use
translation software and

00:29:01.870 --> 00:29:03.090
translation technology.

00:29:03.090 --> 00:29:06.760
And the idea of leveraging
past content is already

00:29:06.760 --> 00:29:07.770
widespread.

00:29:07.770 --> 00:29:10.270
This is something that has
exists for decades.

00:29:10.270 --> 00:29:13.910
So the average translation
agency translates about 43,000

00:29:13.910 --> 00:29:14.990
words per day.

00:29:14.990 --> 00:29:17.290
And freelancers have an average
of a little less than

00:29:17.290 --> 00:29:19.360
2,700 words per day.

00:29:19.360 --> 00:29:22.710
We asked freelancers and
translation agencies, how many

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:25.760
words are brand new words
translated for the first time

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:29.650
without using any translation
memory software?

00:29:29.650 --> 00:29:32.620
The rate for both was
almost identical.

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:37.000
It's about 60%, which means
that 40% of what they're

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.140
translating is using translation
memory--

00:29:40.140 --> 00:29:42.770
is relying on past translation
work that's already been done

00:29:42.770 --> 00:29:44.340
in the past.

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:46.410
So when we talk about
technology replacing

00:29:46.410 --> 00:29:49.320
translation, think about
these figures.

00:29:49.320 --> 00:29:53.250
Technology already is helping
replace about 40% of the human

00:29:53.250 --> 00:29:56.080
translation work that used
to be done in the past.

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:58.560
It's just being done by a
slightly different technology

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:01.920
than automatic translation.

00:30:01.920 --> 00:30:07.350
So, is technology going to
replace human translators?

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:09.210
This is a question we get
asked all the time.

00:30:09.210 --> 00:30:11.820
And I always ask, has accounting
software made

00:30:11.820 --> 00:30:14.320
accountants obsolete?

00:30:14.320 --> 00:30:15.830
Has medical diagnostic software

00:30:15.830 --> 00:30:17.980
made doctors obsolete?

00:30:17.980 --> 00:30:20.660
Has legal software made
lawyers obsolete?

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:23.220
So, why do we think that
translation software would

00:30:23.220 --> 00:30:24.380
make translators obsolete?

00:30:24.380 --> 00:30:25.970
Especially when we've been
using translation

00:30:25.970 --> 00:30:28.370
software for decades.

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:32.170
That's a question that I think
all of us should ask.

00:30:32.170 --> 00:30:36.330
These fields are constantly
evolving, and so is the field

00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:37.130
of translation.

00:30:37.130 --> 00:30:39.580
And as I mentioned, those 26,000
companies, they're not

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:41.050
just made up of translators.

00:30:41.050 --> 00:30:42.780
They're made up of salespeople,
they're made up

00:30:42.780 --> 00:30:44.860
of marketing directors, they're
made up of software

00:30:44.860 --> 00:30:47.340
engineers, they're made up of
all kinds of people-- human

00:30:47.340 --> 00:30:48.800
resources staff.

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:50.630
Many, many people are employed
in this industry.

00:30:50.630 --> 00:30:53.140
It's not just translators that
would have to be replaced.

00:30:56.140 --> 00:31:02.760
Language is categorized as the
epitome of human intelligence.

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:05.980
So, how many of you are familiar
with the Turing test?

00:31:05.980 --> 00:31:07.420
Many of you.

00:31:07.420 --> 00:31:12.190
So the Turing test looks at the
machine's ability to use

00:31:12.190 --> 00:31:13.840
language as a human would.

00:31:13.840 --> 00:31:15.820
And this is considered to be the
ultimate test of whether

00:31:15.820 --> 00:31:19.290
machines can have human
intelligence.

00:31:19.290 --> 00:31:21.850
So, the questions that we can
ask ourselves when it comes

00:31:21.850 --> 00:31:25.450
to, can a machine replace
a human translator?

00:31:25.450 --> 00:31:29.020
Can a machine use language
like a human can?

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:31.520
Can a machine debate politics?

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:34.290
Can a machine write poetry?

00:31:34.290 --> 00:31:36.960
Can a machine flirt
with someone?

00:31:36.960 --> 00:31:40.290
Can a machine tell jokes?

00:31:40.290 --> 00:31:42.550
In just one language,
can a machine do

00:31:42.550 --> 00:31:44.510
any of those things?

00:31:44.510 --> 00:31:46.820
Maybe we can get to a point
where a machine can do some of

00:31:46.820 --> 00:31:49.560
those things in one language,
but we're not just dealing

00:31:49.560 --> 00:31:50.520
with one language.

00:31:50.520 --> 00:31:53.900
We're dealing with thousands
of languages.

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:57.910
So the answer that we need to
remember, when we're asked

00:31:57.910 --> 00:32:02.860
this question of can machines
replace humans in translation,

00:32:02.860 --> 00:32:05.430
is that we still have
a long way to go.

00:32:05.430 --> 00:32:06.670
A really long way.

00:32:06.670 --> 00:32:08.860
Google Translate is available
today in 65

00:32:08.860 --> 00:32:11.080
languages plus English.

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:14.240
But there are between 6,000
and 7,000 languages in the

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:16.340
world today.

00:32:16.340 --> 00:32:18.490
And there's just one big problem
when it comes to

00:32:18.490 --> 00:32:21.040
thinking about extending Google
Translate into all of

00:32:21.040 --> 00:32:22.290
those languages.

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:28.870
Only 2,261 have writing
systems.

00:32:28.870 --> 00:32:32.990
The rest of them are
spoken or signed.

00:32:32.990 --> 00:32:35.000
There are hundreds of
sign languages.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:38.960
There are 18 in Latin
America alone.

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:42.350
So written translation
is really not enough.

00:32:42.350 --> 00:32:43.510
It's hardly sufficient.

00:32:43.510 --> 00:32:46.070
The majority of the languages
are spoken or signed.

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:51.810
So, even if we could address
all of those issues, and we

00:32:51.810 --> 00:32:55.260
can imagine that we can do
automatic translation for

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:58.610
spoken, and written, and signed
language-- and all of

00:32:58.610 --> 00:33:00.070
those languages--

00:33:00.070 --> 00:33:01.880
there's one more problem.

00:33:01.880 --> 00:33:05.950
We would have to hit a big Pause
button on human language

00:33:05.950 --> 00:33:06.680
development.

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:08.700
We would say, freeze,
everybody!

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:09.890
No more jokes.

00:33:09.890 --> 00:33:11.330
No more plays on words.

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:12.840
No more new invented terms.

00:33:12.840 --> 00:33:14.400
Everybody has to stop.

00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:17.530
And we are going to mine all
text ever produced in every

00:33:17.530 --> 00:33:19.260
single language.

00:33:19.260 --> 00:33:22.080
And we are going to analyze
all language variations

00:33:22.080 --> 00:33:25.880
currently spoken by every
human being on Earth.

00:33:25.880 --> 00:33:27.650
And then we're going to
translate it into and out of

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:33.220
6,000 to 7,000 languages that
exist throughout the world.

00:33:33.220 --> 00:33:36.490
As soon as we hit that Play
button again, the need for

00:33:36.490 --> 00:33:37.740
human translators returns.

00:33:41.180 --> 00:33:44.710
So, this is an image of a
blacksmith that I took just a

00:33:44.710 --> 00:33:48.960
couple of years ago, in a very
small town in rural Illinois,

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:50.460
near where I grew up--

00:33:50.460 --> 00:33:55.690
in New Salem, which is a
Lincoln Heritage site.

00:33:55.690 --> 00:33:58.770
And this is a working
blacksmith.

00:33:58.770 --> 00:34:01.900
I was surprised to learn that
there are still about 11,000

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:05.600
working blacksmiths in the
United States today, similar

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:08.090
to the number of professional
translators that are members

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:11.320
of the American Translators
Association.

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:14.830
Now, not all of them are
full-time blacksmiths that are

00:34:14.830 --> 00:34:15.880
paid to do that work.

00:34:15.880 --> 00:34:18.900
And a lot of what they're doing
is custom work, custom

00:34:18.900 --> 00:34:20.440
forging for--

00:34:20.440 --> 00:34:24.060
making little brackets to hang
curtains and doorknobs and

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:25.310
things like that.

00:34:25.310 --> 00:34:28.639
A lot of that work is very
artisanal, very specialized,

00:34:28.639 --> 00:34:29.929
very customized.

00:34:29.929 --> 00:34:32.489
But some of them
do still exist.

00:34:32.489 --> 00:34:35.219
As I mentioned, many of
the blacksmiths--

00:34:35.219 --> 00:34:37.100
this field evolved, the
profession evolved, just like

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:39.179
the profession of translation
is evolving.

00:34:39.179 --> 00:34:42.389
But some still do this work the
very same way that it was

00:34:42.389 --> 00:34:45.120
done many, many years ago.

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:47.889
So, do translators really have
anything in common with

00:34:47.889 --> 00:34:49.219
blacksmiths?

00:34:49.219 --> 00:34:51.580
Well, translators don't
work in total

00:34:51.580 --> 00:34:53.230
isolation, like I mentioned.

00:34:53.230 --> 00:34:56.409
They're not separate from
all of these other jobs.

00:34:56.409 --> 00:35:00.190
They are part of an ecosystem,
part of a community.

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:04.190
And it's unlikely that we will
ever be able to mass produce

00:35:04.190 --> 00:35:07.290
content the way that you can
mass produce a box of nails in

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:08.360
a standard way.

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:11.930
And as I mentioned, 40% of
current translation work

00:35:11.930 --> 00:35:14.020
leverages past work already.

00:35:14.020 --> 00:35:17.160
So, if we are in a process of
replacing human translators--

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:20.100
we're already in the midst
of that process--

00:35:20.100 --> 00:35:22.590
60% of the work that translators
are doing today

00:35:22.590 --> 00:35:26.330
still entails custom forging,
if we want to use the

00:35:26.330 --> 00:35:28.190
blacksmith metaphor.

00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:32.220
So, this profession is already
in the midst of evolving.

00:35:32.220 --> 00:35:35.160
So, are translators the
new blacksmiths?

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:38.850
Well, I believe that much like
blacksmiths pushed us into the

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:41.450
industrial age, into the
Industrial Revolution,

00:35:41.450 --> 00:35:45.840
translation is pushing us past
the information age and we are

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:47.690
moving now into the information

00:35:47.690 --> 00:35:50.290
transformation age.

00:35:50.290 --> 00:35:53.950
Whatever shape the next
revolution we have takes--

00:35:53.950 --> 00:35:56.440
a lot of people have referred
to this as the Information

00:35:56.440 --> 00:35:58.290
Revolution--

00:35:58.290 --> 00:35:59.910
translation has to
play a part.

00:35:59.910 --> 00:36:03.480
We can't talk about access to
information unless we talk

00:36:03.480 --> 00:36:05.030
about translation, unless
we talk about

00:36:05.030 --> 00:36:08.270
the language component.

00:36:08.270 --> 00:36:11.140
So translation will be critical
in helping us achieve

00:36:11.140 --> 00:36:12.800
a better quality of life.

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:15.580
Now, we did a study recently
at Common Sense Advisory on

00:36:15.580 --> 00:36:17.600
the need for translation
in Africa.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:19.740
And this was a study that was
commissioned by Translators

00:36:19.740 --> 00:36:21.460
Without Borders.

00:36:21.460 --> 00:36:26.230
And we were surprised to see
that so many respondents told

00:36:26.230 --> 00:36:30.170
us that translation would effect
virtually every aspect

00:36:30.170 --> 00:36:31.030
of their life.

00:36:31.030 --> 00:36:36.460
Political inclusion, health
information, information about

00:36:36.460 --> 00:36:38.600
how to prevent conflict.

00:36:38.600 --> 00:36:40.750
People even said that they
thought it would reduce-- more

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:42.480
access to translated information
would reduce

00:36:42.480 --> 00:36:44.280
violent conflict.

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:47.610
They also said that it would
prevent the loss of life, of

00:36:47.610 --> 00:36:48.640
loved ones.

00:36:48.640 --> 00:36:51.130
Just having information
to basic--

00:36:51.130 --> 00:36:53.730
access to basic information
about how to prevent certain

00:36:53.730 --> 00:36:56.700
health concerns and health
conditions would have had a

00:36:56.700 --> 00:36:58.430
tremendous impact.

00:36:58.430 --> 00:37:00.710
So when we think about the
Industrial Revolution, how it

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:03.680
led us to a new quality of life,
I truly believe that

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:06.300
translation, for many people who
don't have much access to

00:37:06.300 --> 00:37:09.410
information, especially in their
native languages, can

00:37:09.410 --> 00:37:11.700
definitely impact their lives.

00:37:11.700 --> 00:37:15.040
We have data that
shows us this.

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:19.210
I don't think that content
is king anymore.

00:37:19.210 --> 00:37:22.240
I believe that the ability
to transform content, to

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:25.550
intelligently use that
information, to customize it,

00:37:25.550 --> 00:37:30.290
is truly the new king
or maybe queen.

00:37:30.290 --> 00:37:35.560
Speaking of kings, I was
looking for stories and

00:37:35.560 --> 00:37:37.970
information about blacksmiths,
and I came across this story

00:37:37.970 --> 00:37:39.400
about King Arthur.

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:43.400
So, King Arthur summoned all the
artisans and asked them to

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:46.080
explain why their work was
important to building Camelot.

00:37:46.080 --> 00:37:49.280
He asked them to justify
their position.

00:37:49.280 --> 00:37:51.120
So he brought in the tailor, he
brought in the carpenter,

00:37:51.120 --> 00:37:52.490
he brought in the
stonemason, the

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:54.220
goldsmith, and other artisans.

00:37:54.220 --> 00:37:56.930
And each of them made a very
strong case to him for why

00:37:56.930 --> 00:38:00.200
their work was important.

00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:02.280
And he asked them where
they got their tools.

00:38:02.280 --> 00:38:07.000
And each one of them said,
the blacksmith.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.950
So Arthur asked the
blacksmith, and

00:38:09.950 --> 00:38:12.736
who makes your tools?

00:38:12.736 --> 00:38:17.300
And the blacksmith said, Sire,
I make my own tools.

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:20.430
That is my craft.

00:38:20.430 --> 00:38:23.370
Now, remember that American
Translators Association

00:38:23.370 --> 00:38:26.170
session that I pointed out,
where translators are being

00:38:26.170 --> 00:38:28.320
taught to create their own
statistical machine

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:30.480
translation engines?

00:38:30.480 --> 00:38:34.560
Talk about making
your own tools

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:35.810
Is that our craft?

00:38:35.810 --> 00:38:39.360
Is that the craft of translators
for the future?

00:38:39.360 --> 00:38:42.046
"And the kindly King moved the
humble blacksmith to the head

00:38:42.046 --> 00:38:45.830
of his table, as he had made
all the tools for all the

00:38:45.830 --> 00:38:50.410
trades." I truly believe that
translators are in the process

00:38:50.410 --> 00:38:53.200
of making their own information
tools, whether

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:55.490
that is contributing to their
own translation memory

00:38:55.490 --> 00:38:58.510
databases, or simply producing
translations that are being

00:38:58.510 --> 00:39:02.790
mined by statistical machine
translation engines.

00:39:02.790 --> 00:39:06.200
And these are tools that can
truly open up a door to human

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:09.050
rights and to a civilization
that we can't

00:39:09.050 --> 00:39:10.140
even describe today.

00:39:10.140 --> 00:39:12.990
We haven't even imagined what
it will be like for so many

00:39:12.990 --> 00:39:15.610
people who don't have access
to information, and can't

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:18.560
understand what it's like to
benefit from that information

00:39:18.560 --> 00:39:20.110
in a language that they
can truly understand.

00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:25.850
So, I've told you about the
book and the fact that I

00:39:25.850 --> 00:39:29.150
believe that translation not
only shapes our lives and

00:39:29.150 --> 00:39:32.580
transforms the world, but I also
believe that translation

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:36.540
truly defines our future.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:39.960
I think when we talk about
access to information, we

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:42.090
really have to think about
access to information as a

00:39:42.090 --> 00:39:44.160
human right.

00:39:44.160 --> 00:39:47.630
And until we can unlock that
information for those 6,000 to

00:39:47.630 --> 00:39:52.660
7,000 languages, we truly are
not providing equal access to

00:39:52.660 --> 00:39:54.860
everybody who needs it.

00:39:54.860 --> 00:39:57.320
So that's why I believe
translation matters, and

00:39:57.320 --> 00:40:00.340
that's why I believe it will
have an important effect on

00:40:00.340 --> 00:40:01.170
the way we live our lives.

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:04.800
Not only today, but
in the future.

00:40:04.800 --> 00:40:08.495
So, with that, I will be happy
to take your questions

00:40:08.495 --> 00:40:09.745
[APPLAUSE].

00:40:16.130 --> 00:40:19.920
MALE SPEAKER: So, I think I want
to put together a couple

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:21.770
thoughts, because you covered
a lot of ground.

00:40:21.770 --> 00:40:26.000
But the 6,000 to 7,000
languages--

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:28.340
I think that includes
a fair number of

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:30.780
dead and archaic languages?

00:40:30.780 --> 00:40:31.050
NATALY KELLY: No.

00:40:31.050 --> 00:40:33.170
Those are all languages that are
spoken, but many of them

00:40:33.170 --> 00:40:34.320
are endangered.

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:34.700
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:40:34.700 --> 00:40:35.950
NATALY KELLY: Mm-hmm.

00:40:37.900 --> 00:40:40.660
MALE SPEAKER: Also, the
statistics that are based on

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:44.910
the volume of translation, a lot
of that is driven by the

00:40:44.910 --> 00:40:49.140
amount of content that's being
translated, not necessarily

00:40:49.140 --> 00:40:49.870
the demands.

00:40:49.870 --> 00:40:53.480
Because I think most of us in
this room know that we have a

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:57.360
number of companies that like
to just translate whatever

00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:00.060
there have gotten, don't always
pay attention to the

00:41:00.060 --> 00:41:03.820
quality of their content,
and so forth.

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:07.320
I see pressure in
many countries--

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:08.680
China, India--

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:10.400
as a part of solving--

00:41:10.400 --> 00:41:12.880
and also in Africa--

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:16.730
solving their literacy issues
and their communication issues

00:41:16.730 --> 00:41:18.570
by moving towards--

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:22.540
well, first, education, but then
also standardization and

00:41:22.540 --> 00:41:26.630
centralization of their
population's ability to speak

00:41:26.630 --> 00:41:27.820
fewer languages.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.880
Moving in that direction.

00:41:29.880 --> 00:41:33.700
So, between that and the number
of languages that are

00:41:33.700 --> 00:41:38.810
dying every year, it would seem
that there's also a trend

00:41:38.810 --> 00:41:44.370
that is somehow ignored in
your discussion of having

00:41:44.370 --> 00:41:47.490
actually fewer working
languages in

00:41:47.490 --> 00:41:49.480
the world over time.

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:51.710
Not that translation
would go away.

00:41:51.710 --> 00:41:55.120
But you can't just use the
numbers that are based on

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:57.990
content and costs--

00:41:57.990 --> 00:41:59.180
cost demand.

00:41:59.180 --> 00:42:01.840
So I wonder if you'd address
some of those points.

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:03.290
NATALY KELLY: Sure.

00:42:03.290 --> 00:42:07.060
So, this is a common question
that we're asked a lot.

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:09.480
Are global languages
taking over and

00:42:09.480 --> 00:42:11.420
making some of those--

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:15.530
language number 2,497
and so on--

00:42:15.530 --> 00:42:16.580
less important?

00:42:16.580 --> 00:42:19.470
Because more people can
use an interlanguage--

00:42:19.470 --> 00:42:21.970
one of these large
global languages.

00:42:21.970 --> 00:42:26.020
What is happening is that a
lot of communities now can

00:42:26.020 --> 00:42:29.100
communicate much more easily
than they could in the past.

00:42:29.100 --> 00:42:33.540
So, yes, there is a push for
literacy, even in languages

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:35.400
that don't have a
writing system.

00:42:35.400 --> 00:42:40.330
And there's this-- in my view--
archaic desire to force

00:42:40.330 --> 00:42:43.850
literacy upon people,
when in some cases

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:45.710
that's not that necessary.

00:42:45.710 --> 00:42:48.180
If they can communicate with
video-based, audio-based

00:42:48.180 --> 00:42:50.990
information, why do they
need to be forced to

00:42:50.990 --> 00:42:52.500
have a writing system?

00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:57.050
Maybe it's better to use audio
and video information, where a

00:42:57.050 --> 00:43:01.270
lot more nuance and a lot more
information-- it's much richer

00:43:01.270 --> 00:43:02.660
information to begin with.

00:43:02.660 --> 00:43:04.940
So maybe they can
skip that step.

00:43:04.940 --> 00:43:08.500
It used to be that writing was
very important, because that

00:43:08.500 --> 00:43:12.030
was a fast way to disseminate
lots of information.

00:43:12.030 --> 00:43:15.090
But now we can do the same thing
much more efficiently,

00:43:15.090 --> 00:43:18.010
in a lot of ways, with
video information.

00:43:18.010 --> 00:43:20.480
So one thing that we do at
Common Sense Advisory is look

00:43:20.480 --> 00:43:23.250
at the stats of languages on
the web, and which ones are

00:43:23.250 --> 00:43:24.540
becoming more important.

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:27.190
Every year we do a large-scale
study on this.

00:43:27.190 --> 00:43:29.100
And one thing that we're
noticing is that these less

00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:31.450
common languages are becoming
more and more

00:43:31.450 --> 00:43:32.280
important each year.

00:43:32.280 --> 00:43:34.920
And we have that long tail of
languages effect that I'm sure

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:36.740
many of you are familiar with.

00:43:36.740 --> 00:43:40.240
So, yes, there are efforts in
many countries to standardize.

00:43:40.240 --> 00:43:45.010
And there are efforts to kind
of go toward one language,

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:47.920
gravitate toward a language of
power, a language that is

00:43:47.920 --> 00:43:52.080
traditionally the language of
people in society that are

00:43:52.080 --> 00:43:54.510
usually the ones who
hold the resources.

00:43:54.510 --> 00:43:57.300
But there are also a lot of
efforts to preserve native

00:43:57.300 --> 00:44:00.470
languages, and to allow people
to use the language that's

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:02.260
most familiar to them.

00:44:02.260 --> 00:44:04.350
So, I don't think that that
trend is going to go away.

00:44:04.350 --> 00:44:06.370
I think it's only going
to increase.

00:44:06.370 --> 00:44:08.030
Because all of the companies--

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:10.660
I know many of you work for
large global companies--

00:44:10.660 --> 00:44:13.680
and who are you competing with
when you're going into some of

00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:14.300
those markets?

00:44:14.300 --> 00:44:16.360
You're competing with
local competitors,

00:44:16.360 --> 00:44:17.460
for the most part.

00:44:17.460 --> 00:44:21.030
And a lot of them are founded
by people who speak some of

00:44:21.030 --> 00:44:22.170
those minority languages.

00:44:22.170 --> 00:44:25.480
And many of them will have
bilingual websites, and

00:44:25.480 --> 00:44:27.530
websites in some of
those languages.

00:44:27.530 --> 00:44:29.740
So, every country is slightly
different, of course, with

00:44:29.740 --> 00:44:31.100
regard to their language policy,
and with regard to

00:44:31.100 --> 00:44:33.950
their preferences, and with
regard to who's in power at

00:44:33.950 --> 00:44:35.000
the moment.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:38.340
But I see a lot of small
languages fighting.

00:44:38.340 --> 00:44:41.650
And I see a lot of them
creating content.

00:44:41.650 --> 00:44:44.580
And really, if they have the
operating systems to be able

00:44:44.580 --> 00:44:47.170
to create content, that is what
is opening the door for

00:44:47.170 --> 00:44:50.810
them to be able to do that, at
least in a digital fashion.

00:44:50.810 --> 00:44:53.130
So I'm not sure I answered your
question exactly, but

00:44:53.130 --> 00:44:54.655
it's a complicated one.

