I just have a quick question.

00:48:33.185 --> 00:48:35.440
It's pretty basic, actually.

00:48:35.440 --> 00:48:38.140
Does highly technical language,
such as legalese or

00:48:38.140 --> 00:48:40.780
medical jargon, change
as quickly

00:48:40.780 --> 00:48:42.320
as colloquial language?

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:46.500
And if so, in your research,
have you found it easier--

00:48:46.500 --> 00:48:50.240
or even possible-- to
standardize that content?

00:48:50.240 --> 00:48:54.130
As opposed to humor and other
things like intoxicado as you

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:57.010
mentioned early on in
your presentation.

00:48:57.010 --> 00:48:59.640
NATALY KELLY: That type of
terminology tends to evolve

00:48:59.640 --> 00:49:00.790
even more quickly.

00:49:00.790 --> 00:49:01.970
It depends on the field.

00:49:01.970 --> 00:49:05.150
But I recently was at a
conference for the World Bank,

00:49:05.150 --> 00:49:08.270
and I was mentioning that the
standard rate of productivity

00:49:08.270 --> 00:49:09.900
for translators for decades--

00:49:09.900 --> 00:49:12.315
since I entered the profession
at least-- was always 2,500

00:49:12.315 --> 00:49:13.820
words per day.

00:49:13.820 --> 00:49:17.940
And the translators from the
World Bank told me, well, our

00:49:17.940 --> 00:49:21.920
guideline is about 2,000 words
per day, because we have to

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:24.990
translate all kinds of new
financial terminology that's

00:49:24.990 --> 00:49:30.000
being invented on the fly, and
new program names, new offices

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.300
that are being created in
different countries, and

00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:33.260
things like that.

00:49:33.260 --> 00:49:35.810
So, it really depends
on the field.

00:49:35.810 --> 00:49:38.670
But that kind of terminology
does really represent a

00:49:38.670 --> 00:49:40.840
challenge for translators,
because many times they are

00:49:40.840 --> 00:49:44.120
inventing the terms and
in another language.

00:49:44.120 --> 00:49:45.460
So it takes a lot of research.

00:49:45.460 --> 00:49:48.240
It takes how can I come up with
the perfect word for this

00:49:48.240 --> 00:49:51.490
that's going to be used from
now on by this official

00:49:51.490 --> 00:49:53.550
government body like
the World Bank?

00:49:53.550 --> 00:49:55.320
So, that kind of terminology--

00:49:55.320 --> 00:49:56.976
and in some fields--
and it depends on

00:49:56.976 --> 00:49:58.120
the language as well.

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:00.810
Because some languages have
pretty strict rules about new

00:50:00.810 --> 00:50:02.490
terminology entering
the language, at

00:50:02.490 --> 00:50:04.010
least in written form.

00:50:04.010 --> 00:50:06.510
And they tend to be a little
bit less responsive to what

00:50:06.510 --> 00:50:08.460
people are actually using on the
ground, if they have all

00:50:08.460 --> 00:50:10.880
those kinds of bodies dictating
what people

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:12.460
can and can't say.

00:50:12.460 --> 00:50:15.450
So you can kind of tell what
side I'm on when it comes to

00:50:15.450 --> 00:50:16.650
those kinds of organizations.

00:50:16.650 --> 00:50:19.000
But it depends on
many factors.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:22.350
But the short answer is that the
specialized groups tend to

00:50:22.350 --> 00:50:26.230
evolve their specialized
areas more quickly.

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:30.030
MALE SPEAKER: In the course of
looking at scenarios for

00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:32.670
companies that have several
target languages--

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:32.870
NATALY KELLY: Mm-hmm.

00:50:32.870 --> 00:50:35.500
MALE SPEAKER: Did you look
into any interest in

00:50:35.500 --> 00:50:40.180
simplified or pivot English
as a intermediate step?

00:50:40.180 --> 00:50:41.770
And can you comment on that?

00:50:41.770 --> 00:50:43.340
NATALY KELLY: Yeah.

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:46.320
Well, we haven't looked
specifically at pivot English

00:50:46.320 --> 00:50:47.860
or simplified English.

00:50:47.860 --> 00:50:50.330
But we have looked at English
as a pivot language.

00:50:50.330 --> 00:50:52.470
So for those of you who are not
familiar, what's happening

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:54.810
is, because the volume of
translation has been

00:50:54.810 --> 00:50:57.410
increasing for a lot of
languages and the translation

00:50:57.410 --> 00:50:59.450
profession has not evolved
that quickly in some

00:50:59.450 --> 00:51:00.200
countries--

00:51:00.200 --> 00:51:01.270
China is one example.

00:51:01.270 --> 00:51:03.640
India is another.

00:51:03.640 --> 00:51:06.550
What's happening is a lot of
companies have to translate

00:51:06.550 --> 00:51:09.260
into English first and
then into Chinese.

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:11.600
So there aren't enough
translators between, say,

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:12.880
Italian and Chinese.

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:16.480
So they're going Italian into
English, English into Chinese.

00:51:16.480 --> 00:51:19.670
And this is happening for
other languages as well.

00:51:19.670 --> 00:51:21.660
So yes, we have looked
at that.

00:51:21.660 --> 00:51:24.940
And it's problematic
for many reasons.

00:51:24.940 --> 00:51:29.120
One, the cost of doing that
is twice as expensive.

00:51:29.120 --> 00:51:32.060
And second, the quality degrades
when you have to

00:51:32.060 --> 00:51:34.400
translate a translation.

00:51:34.400 --> 00:51:35.820
So that is a concern.

00:51:35.820 --> 00:51:37.220
We've written quite
a bit about that.

00:51:37.220 --> 00:51:39.080
And it is a problem.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:41.510
But what we've written about
is that the fields--

00:51:41.510 --> 00:51:42.190
the professions--

00:51:42.190 --> 00:51:43.870
are not maturing fast enough.

00:51:43.870 --> 00:51:45.150
They're not keeping up.

00:51:45.150 --> 00:51:46.880
And it's a difficult problem.

00:51:46.880 --> 00:51:48.940
Because, in markets like
China, when I talk to

00:51:48.940 --> 00:51:51.870
companies in China, they tell
me, well, if I find someone

00:51:51.870 --> 00:51:54.140
who has good enough English to
be a translator, or good

00:51:54.140 --> 00:51:56.860
enough German or French, they
go and specialize in

00:51:56.860 --> 00:52:00.330
international business, where
they can make more money.

00:52:00.330 --> 00:52:04.580
And some translation agencies in
China actually told me that

00:52:04.580 --> 00:52:07.210
they can't keep translators long
enough, because some of

00:52:07.210 --> 00:52:09.080
them will work for a few months,
they make enough money

00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:11.580
that they go on vacation for a
couple months, and then they

00:52:11.580 --> 00:52:12.130
never come back.

00:52:12.130 --> 00:52:14.870
And then they go work for
a different agency.

00:52:14.870 --> 00:52:17.840
And others are saying that they
can't find enough talent

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:20.490
that's willing to work for the
wages that they can offer,

00:52:20.490 --> 00:52:24.490
because their standards are
higher, and their customers

00:52:24.490 --> 00:52:25.850
expect better quality.

00:52:25.850 --> 00:52:27.600
So, it is a real challenge.

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:28.890
We're seeing that for
many different

00:52:28.890 --> 00:52:31.370
languages around the world.

00:52:31.370 --> 00:52:31.780
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hey.

00:52:31.780 --> 00:52:33.070
NATALY KELLY: Hey.

00:52:33.070 --> 00:52:35.270
FEMALE SPEAKER: Can you share
with us the most interesting

00:52:35.270 --> 00:52:37.700
or surprising reaction you've
had to your book?

00:52:37.700 --> 00:52:40.532
NATALY KELLY: [LAUGHS]

00:52:40.532 --> 00:52:43.570
You know, that's a
good question.

00:52:43.570 --> 00:52:47.830
I think the most surprising
reaction I've had--

00:52:47.830 --> 00:52:49.270
well, there's a few things
that-- there are a few that

00:52:49.270 --> 00:52:51.880
come to mind.

00:52:51.880 --> 00:52:54.240
I think the most interesting
thing was speaking at the

00:52:54.240 --> 00:52:55.960
Jimmy Carter Library.

00:52:55.960 --> 00:52:59.340
And a lot of people came to that
who had no background in

00:52:59.340 --> 00:53:00.280
translation whatsoever.

00:53:00.280 --> 00:53:02.590
In fact, it's kind of a treat
for me to speak to people who

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:04.600
actually deal with translation,
understand a lot

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:05.810
about translation.

00:53:05.810 --> 00:53:10.050
In that group-- in most of the
public talks and signings that

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:11.110
I've been doing--

00:53:11.110 --> 00:53:13.400
a lot of people are coming just
from the general public.

00:53:13.400 --> 00:53:15.950
People in the bookstore
who just wander over.

00:53:15.950 --> 00:53:18.970
And I think that's
really exciting.

00:53:18.970 --> 00:53:21.090
It has been surprising for me
how many people are interested

00:53:21.090 --> 00:53:21.770
in the topic.

00:53:21.770 --> 00:53:25.060
And one person actually told me
that they found a copy of

00:53:25.060 --> 00:53:28.680
my book in a Barnes and Noble
in Louisville, Kentucky

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:31.290
[LAUGHS], and that really
made me happy.

00:53:31.290 --> 00:53:34.520
Because I think the message that
we need to get out is to

00:53:34.520 --> 00:53:36.850
all the people who don't work
in languages, and all the

00:53:36.850 --> 00:53:39.770
people who are mono-lingual and
don't know a thing about

00:53:39.770 --> 00:53:41.230
all other languages.

00:53:41.230 --> 00:53:43.730
If they can start to take an
interest and start to see that

00:53:43.730 --> 00:53:46.150
translation affects their lives,
I think there'll be a

00:53:46.150 --> 00:53:48.660
lot more support for
the industry.

00:53:48.660 --> 00:53:52.380
And in writing this book, our
big goal was to really make it

00:53:52.380 --> 00:53:54.810
like Freakonomics
for translation.

00:53:54.810 --> 00:53:57.430
You know, take a topic that
people think is dry and boring

00:53:57.430 --> 00:53:58.790
and not really--

00:53:58.790 --> 00:54:02.760
doesn't really affect me, and
to make it fun and exciting,

00:54:02.760 --> 00:54:05.430
and make it seem real, and make
it seem like it affects

00:54:05.430 --> 00:54:06.650
their lives, because it does.

00:54:06.650 --> 00:54:07.490
[LAUGHS].

00:54:07.490 --> 00:54:10.400
So, I don't have any
real shockers.

00:54:10.400 --> 00:54:16.010
But that's pretty much my
impressions so far.

00:54:16.010 --> 00:54:17.700
Thank you.

00:54:17.700 --> 00:54:19.040
MALE SPEAKER: That reminds me.

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:22.020
It's not a surprise, but I
noticed one of your most

00:54:22.020 --> 00:54:24.420
recent Tweets that you got
a thank-you letter from

00:54:24.420 --> 00:54:28.270
President Carter and Rosalynn
for your nice memories of them

00:54:28.270 --> 00:54:29.920
in the book.

00:54:29.920 --> 00:54:30.757
NATALY KELLY: Yes.

00:54:30.757 --> 00:54:31.890
MALE SPEAKER: That was--

00:54:31.890 --> 00:54:33.350
NATALY KELLY: That was-- well,
I guess that was a shock.

00:54:33.350 --> 00:54:33.890
Yes.

00:54:33.890 --> 00:54:35.320
That was my big shock.

00:54:35.320 --> 00:54:37.060
I'm still a little shaking
when I think about that.

00:54:37.060 --> 00:54:38.920
I didn't expect to receive
a letter from

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:40.900
President Carter himself.

00:54:40.900 --> 00:54:43.540
I did a whole talk at the
Library about what he had done

00:54:43.540 --> 00:54:46.750
throughout his administration,
his short time before he was

00:54:46.750 --> 00:54:49.560
involuntarily retired,
as he puts it.

00:54:49.560 --> 00:54:53.190
And he actually did a lot for
language access, and did a lot

00:54:53.190 --> 00:54:57.520
for the deaf community in the
United States, and a lot for

00:54:57.520 --> 00:54:59.480
court interpreting, and
lots of different

00:54:59.480 --> 00:55:02.146
areas of language access.

00:55:02.146 --> 00:55:02.840
So--

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:03.670
MALE SPEAKER: A nice man.

00:55:03.670 --> 00:55:04.660
His mom was nice, too.

00:55:04.660 --> 00:55:05.670
Ms. Lillian.

00:55:05.670 --> 00:55:06.580
NATALY KELLY: Aww.

00:55:06.580 --> 00:55:08.260
[LAUGHS].

00:55:08.260 --> 00:55:10.850
MALE SPEAKER: Hey, thank
you for the talk.

00:55:10.850 --> 00:55:12.540
You already addressed
this somewhat,

00:55:12.540 --> 00:55:15.580
but I have a question.

00:55:15.580 --> 00:55:17.630
Do you know Duolingo?

00:55:17.630 --> 00:55:22.660
Duolingo is a new technology.

00:55:22.660 --> 00:55:25.690
It's very, very innovative.

00:55:25.690 --> 00:55:30.000
It combines language learning
and crowdsourced translation.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:34.820
Do you think these kind of new
technologies can change how

00:55:34.820 --> 00:55:37.520
translation is done?

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:41.830
NATALY KELLY: Well, I have not
talked with the developers of

00:55:41.830 --> 00:55:42.930
Duolingo personally.

00:55:42.930 --> 00:55:45.520
But I have been watching what
they're doing, and all of us

00:55:45.520 --> 00:55:48.380
on the research team at Common
Sense Advisor are constantly

00:55:48.380 --> 00:55:50.690
taking briefings from technology
vendors, and

00:55:50.690 --> 00:55:54.120
tracking what's going on with
products like Duolingo.

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:55.590
And I think it's interesting.

00:55:55.590 --> 00:55:56.140
You know?

00:55:56.140 --> 00:55:58.730
I think it's interesting
what they're doing.

00:55:58.730 --> 00:56:01.330
And a lot of companies are
doing very interesting

00:56:01.330 --> 00:56:02.390
things right now.

00:56:02.390 --> 00:56:05.140
What I think is even more
interesting than what they're

00:56:05.140 --> 00:56:08.290
doing with their technology is
the fact that they're getting

00:56:08.290 --> 00:56:11.770
funding for some of
these things.

00:56:11.770 --> 00:56:15.070
So, we're starting to see a lot
of high-tech startups that

00:56:15.070 --> 00:56:18.880
are attracting interest from
investors and venture capital.

00:56:18.880 --> 00:56:22.970
And I think that is very
interesting, because I haven't

00:56:22.970 --> 00:56:25.570
really seen the business case
being proved for a lot of

00:56:25.570 --> 00:56:26.760
these things yet.

00:56:26.760 --> 00:56:29.690
But what I'm interested in is
the fact that this is raising

00:56:29.690 --> 00:56:30.920
awareness in society at large.

00:56:30.920 --> 00:56:35.140
So, Ashton Kutcher is a backer
of Duolingo, and Tim Ferris.

00:56:35.140 --> 00:56:38.450
And we wrote a post recently
on our blog about all the

00:56:38.450 --> 00:56:41.430
celebrities that are backing
translation technologies.

00:56:41.430 --> 00:56:45.000
You know, Gene Simmons from Kiss
is a backer of Ortsbo.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:48.900
And many people don't realize
that Bono has interest in a

00:56:48.900 --> 00:56:51.290
company called SDI Media--

00:56:51.290 --> 00:56:54.140
which some of you might be
familiar with, if you work in

00:56:54.140 --> 00:56:55.880
film and gaming.

00:56:55.880 --> 00:56:57.840
And they do a lot of the
multilingual subtitling of

00:56:57.840 --> 00:56:58.330
voiceovers.

00:56:58.330 --> 00:57:01.780
So this kind of interest from
high-profile names and venture

00:57:01.780 --> 00:57:04.100
capital, and actually seeing
some real money come into the

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:07.170
industry is, I think,
of great interest.

00:57:07.170 --> 00:57:09.590
And I'll be very interested
to see if those investors

00:57:09.590 --> 00:57:14.470
actually make a profit and
to see what happens.

00:57:14.470 --> 00:57:15.700
This particular model--

00:57:15.700 --> 00:57:18.690
a hybrid of language learning
and translation--

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:19.680
is interesting.

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:24.390
I have been monitoring what's
happening, and we'll see.

00:57:24.390 --> 00:57:27.410
I try to be open-minded when it
comes to any new innovation

00:57:27.410 --> 00:57:30.820
like this, because we are
independent and we kind of

00:57:30.820 --> 00:57:33.210
have to stand back and see
what's happening from a

00:57:33.210 --> 00:57:34.860
broader market perspective.

00:57:34.860 --> 00:57:37.380
So we can't be tied to
any old-fashioned

00:57:37.380 --> 00:57:38.250
ways of doing things.

00:57:38.250 --> 00:57:40.420
We're always looking at, OK,
what are the newest trends?

00:57:40.420 --> 00:57:43.160
And how is this going to
shake up the industry?

00:57:43.160 --> 00:57:45.220
So, we'll see what happens
with Duolingo.

00:57:45.220 --> 00:57:46.620
There's certainly a lot
of buzz about it.

00:57:46.620 --> 00:57:48.356
They're doing a good
job with marketing.

00:57:48.356 --> 00:57:48.832
Yeah.

00:57:48.832 --> 00:57:50.260
[LAUGHS]

00:57:50.260 --> 00:57:51.510
Mm-hmm?

00:57:53.240 --> 00:57:57.200
MALE SPEAKER: Your discussion
about the Beyonce picture

00:57:57.200 --> 00:58:00.150
illustrated very interestingly
the amount of context required

00:58:00.150 --> 00:58:01.330
to understand something.

00:58:01.330 --> 00:58:03.790
Do you have any analogous
examples from your Shuar

00:58:03.790 --> 00:58:08.170
poetry translation as to what
kind of contextual differences

00:58:08.170 --> 00:58:10.012
would need to be explained?

00:58:10.012 --> 00:58:10.370
NATALY KELLY: Oh.

00:58:10.370 --> 00:58:11.380
Too many to list.

00:58:11.380 --> 00:58:13.970
I mean, her culture is so
different from the one that I

00:58:13.970 --> 00:58:14.900
grew up in.

00:58:14.900 --> 00:58:18.670
And there's a single word in
her language that actually

00:58:18.670 --> 00:58:22.300
means "the song that is emitted
through the fragrance

00:58:22.300 --> 00:58:26.680
of a plant." "The song that is
emitted through the fragrance

00:58:26.680 --> 00:58:28.360
of a plant." And I have to think
about it every time I

00:58:28.360 --> 00:58:31.030
say it, because it still
confuses me.

00:58:31.030 --> 00:58:33.590
So that's in one of her poems.

00:58:33.590 --> 00:58:36.030
And I had to figure out how on
Earth to render that into

00:58:36.030 --> 00:58:38.750
English without destroying the
lyrical quality of the poem.

00:58:38.750 --> 00:58:39.630
[LAUGHS]

00:58:39.630 --> 00:58:41.270
So I went with--

00:58:41.270 --> 00:58:43.490
I went around with "sacred song"
and all these different

00:58:43.490 --> 00:58:45.730
things, and it just
doesn't convey it.

00:58:45.730 --> 00:58:48.300
So we ended up putting an
asterisk and an explanation at

00:58:48.300 --> 00:58:48.790
the bottom.

00:58:48.790 --> 00:58:49.280
[LAUGHS]

00:58:49.280 --> 00:58:51.090
Because it's the only
way to give the full

00:58:51.090 --> 00:58:52.530
context to the reader.

00:58:52.530 --> 00:58:54.640
But yeah, there are
many like that.

00:58:54.640 --> 00:58:56.900
But we don't even have to go
to a language like Shuar to

00:58:56.900 --> 00:58:58.560
come up with examples
like that.

00:58:58.560 --> 00:59:03.700
There are tons of examples
like this in all kinds of

00:59:03.700 --> 00:59:06.690
languages, even languages
like Spanish.

00:59:06.690 --> 00:59:07.680
There are words--

00:59:07.680 --> 00:59:09.890
and we have a whole example
in the book of words

00:59:09.890 --> 00:59:11.930
for brown in Spanish.

00:59:11.930 --> 00:59:15.110
And it depends on if you're
describing a bear, or an

00:59:15.110 --> 00:59:17.270
animal, or eyes, or hair.

00:59:17.270 --> 00:59:20.570
What word do you
use for brown?

00:59:20.570 --> 00:59:22.930
And people have asked me, does
that mean that people who

00:59:22.930 --> 00:59:24.960
speak Spanish see shades
of brown that other

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:26.462
people don't see?

00:59:26.462 --> 00:59:27.640
Maybe that's one
of the weirdest

00:59:27.640 --> 00:59:28.710
questions that I got, Mary.

00:59:28.710 --> 00:59:29.940
[LAUGHS]

00:59:29.940 --> 00:59:34.870
But it is fascinating to think
about all of these different

00:59:34.870 --> 00:59:37.830
concepts that we have that are--
even in languages that

00:59:37.830 --> 00:59:40.740
are not linguistically that
distant from each other.

00:59:45.400 --> 00:59:46.600
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you very
much for the talk.

00:59:46.600 --> 00:59:47.660
I had one question.

00:59:47.660 --> 00:59:51.315
When you were explaining how
much power the translators

00:59:51.315 --> 00:59:55.320
have, especially for translators
at the UN, or who

00:59:55.320 --> 00:59:58.370
translate for political
issues--

00:59:58.370 --> 01:00:03.850
I was wondering if there were
any ways for citizens to find

01:00:03.850 --> 01:00:06.860
out afterwards if the
translators had

01:00:06.860 --> 01:00:10.320
any doubt, or any--

01:00:10.320 --> 01:00:11.280
were wondering.

01:00:11.280 --> 01:00:13.390
Like, here, I wasn't
really sure.

01:00:13.390 --> 01:00:17.463
And this could lead
to potential--

01:00:17.463 --> 01:00:18.430
yeah, yeah.

01:00:18.430 --> 01:00:21.440
So I was wondering, were the
tools available for that?

01:00:21.440 --> 01:00:22.440
NATALY KELLY: Oh, yeah.

01:00:22.440 --> 01:00:23.840
Well, it's very hard.

01:00:23.840 --> 01:00:26.080
There are tons of examples that
we mention in the book.

01:00:26.080 --> 01:00:28.970
I'll give you one famous one.

01:00:28.970 --> 01:00:33.680
The words "we will bury you"
that were spoken by Nikita

01:00:33.680 --> 01:00:36.920
Khrushchev were seen
as a threat.

01:00:36.920 --> 01:00:40.750
And people thought that he
literally meant we want to

01:00:40.750 --> 01:00:43.830
kill you, we want to bury you
with a nuclear attack.

01:00:43.830 --> 01:00:46.960
And the phrase that he was
using actually was a more

01:00:46.960 --> 01:00:49.810
common phrase at that time in
Russian that meant something

01:00:49.810 --> 01:00:52.270
like, we will be here even
when you are gone.

01:00:52.270 --> 01:00:54.950
We will outlast you.

01:00:54.950 --> 01:00:57.680
And people have asked me, well,
are you sure that's

01:00:57.680 --> 01:00:58.610
really what that meant?

01:00:58.610 --> 01:01:01.670
And I have given examples of
things we say in English, like

01:01:01.670 --> 01:01:03.510
"he came in dead last."

01:01:03.510 --> 01:01:05.450
Or, "oh, you're killing
me," when

01:01:05.450 --> 01:01:06.880
someone's making you laugh.

01:01:06.880 --> 01:01:11.020
If you think about how we
translate those things, they

01:01:11.020 --> 01:01:13.720
could have a similar impact if
they were mistranslated.

01:01:13.720 --> 01:01:16.700
As for how to go back and find
out if that's exactly what

01:01:16.700 --> 01:01:18.770
someone said, it's a
really hard thing.

01:01:18.770 --> 01:01:20.470
Because you've probably
seen in the media,

01:01:20.470 --> 01:01:21.480
even in recent times.

01:01:21.480 --> 01:01:25.710
When a mistranslation is out
there, that's the story.

01:01:25.710 --> 01:01:29.500
What that person said, that is
pretty much the story that is

01:01:29.500 --> 01:01:30.330
in the news.

01:01:30.330 --> 01:01:33.650
And it's very hard, even when
they issue a correction, to go

01:01:33.650 --> 01:01:35.000
back and change it.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:38.010
And once it's reached the
public, it's really too late

01:01:38.010 --> 01:01:39.210
to go out--

01:01:39.210 --> 01:01:41.110
the public isn't going to be
interested in a story about a

01:01:41.110 --> 01:01:42.910
mistranslation.

01:01:42.910 --> 01:01:44.050
So, it's--

01:01:44.050 --> 01:01:47.730
unfortunately, a lot of what
we hear in the news is

01:01:47.730 --> 01:01:50.210
affected by the translator's
skills and by the

01:01:50.210 --> 01:01:51.680
interpreter's skills.

01:01:51.680 --> 01:01:54.250
So, we have a lot of examples
of that in the book.

01:01:54.250 --> 01:01:57.550
And I was asked the other day,
well, do you have any examples

01:01:57.550 --> 01:02:00.060
of people who mistranslated
those things on purpose?

01:02:00.060 --> 01:02:01.610
[LAUGHS]

01:02:01.610 --> 01:02:02.660
And I'm not--

01:02:02.660 --> 01:02:04.120
I'm not able to go
and interview

01:02:04.120 --> 01:02:05.200
the exact, you know--

01:02:05.200 --> 01:02:06.615
maybe that's another book.

01:02:06.615 --> 01:02:07.080
[LAUGHS]

01:02:07.080 --> 01:02:12.600
But certainly we have plenty
of examples of that.

01:02:12.600 --> 01:02:14.100
And I don't think that
most of those have

01:02:14.100 --> 01:02:14.910
been done on purpose.

01:02:14.910 --> 01:02:17.710
I think the job of the
interpreter is just so

01:02:17.710 --> 01:02:21.610
difficult that a lot of times,
interpreters make mistakes.

01:02:21.610 --> 01:02:25.460
And so that's often the result
when we see some of those

01:02:25.460 --> 01:02:27.262
things in the news.

01:02:27.262 --> 01:02:27.760
Yeah.

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:28.260
TALIA: Hi, Nataly.

01:02:28.260 --> 01:02:30.740
Thank you very much, and
welcome to the Bay, and

01:02:30.740 --> 01:02:34.240
congratulations on
the publication.

01:02:34.240 --> 01:02:36.430
Can you talk a little bit
about the process of

01:02:36.430 --> 01:02:41.760
collecting the stories and the
decision-making of what to

01:02:41.760 --> 01:02:43.080
include and what not?

01:02:43.080 --> 01:02:46.650
And also, whether this book
is going to be translated?

01:02:46.650 --> 01:02:47.550
[LAUGHTER].

01:02:47.550 --> 01:02:49.700
NATALY KELLY: [LAUGHS]

01:02:49.700 --> 01:02:51.290
Leave it to Talia to
come up with two

01:02:51.290 --> 01:02:53.440
really great questions.

01:02:53.440 --> 01:02:57.210
So, as for how we chose the
stories to include in the

01:02:57.210 --> 01:03:01.700
book, it was very important that
we picked stories that

01:03:01.700 --> 01:03:04.080
would reflect a range
of human emotions.

01:03:04.080 --> 01:03:06.650
So we were careful to make sure
that we didn't have too

01:03:06.650 --> 01:03:10.140
many tear-jerkers, and too many
funny mistranslations.

01:03:10.140 --> 01:03:12.880
We wanted to hit every emotion
that we could.

01:03:12.880 --> 01:03:16.090
We also wanted to hit every part
of life that we could.

01:03:16.090 --> 01:03:20.380
So we had stories about
translation of sacred texts

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:22.920
and religion, because we wanted
people to see how

01:03:22.920 --> 01:03:24.500
translation affects their
spiritual life.

01:03:24.500 --> 01:03:28.940
But we also have stories about
translation in mundane topics.

01:03:28.940 --> 01:03:34.060
And things like MAC Cosmetics,
and Harlequin romance novels,

01:03:34.060 --> 01:03:38.330
and Hallmark Cards, and Nescafe,
and all of these

01:03:38.330 --> 01:03:39.960
kinds of things, you
know, products that

01:03:39.960 --> 01:03:41.280
people use every day.

01:03:41.280 --> 01:03:45.820
So we really did try to pick a
range of topics that would hit

01:03:45.820 --> 01:03:47.860
many different areas of life.

01:03:47.860 --> 01:03:50.870
And we also looked at the common
things that people like

01:03:50.870 --> 01:03:52.900
to read about, even
in the newspaper.

01:03:52.900 --> 01:03:57.590
The sports section, the food
section, the politics section.

01:03:57.590 --> 01:03:59.520
Current events.

01:03:59.520 --> 01:04:01.810
Lifestyle, arts, entertainment,

01:04:01.810 --> 01:04:02.610
those kinds of things.

01:04:02.610 --> 01:04:05.920
So, we tried to hit on basically
every aspect of

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:07.450
life-- as many as we could.

01:04:07.450 --> 01:04:10.240
And I wanted to include a
section on science, but that

01:04:10.240 --> 01:04:12.693
didn't seem that interesting
to the average reader.

01:04:12.693 --> 01:04:13.500
[LAUGHS]

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:16.720
But we tried to include as many
as we possibly could.

01:04:16.720 --> 01:04:19.580
As for whether or not the book
will be translated--

01:04:19.580 --> 01:04:22.230
I've had lots of volunteers,
because I have lots of friends

01:04:22.230 --> 01:04:24.120
who are translators.

01:04:24.120 --> 01:04:26.970
This is really a question of the
publisher, and publishing

01:04:26.970 --> 01:04:28.500
rights, and how that
all works.

01:04:28.500 --> 01:04:31.670
So, basically, if a publisher
in another country wants to

01:04:31.670 --> 01:04:33.700
publish the book in another
language, they have to buy the

01:04:33.700 --> 01:04:37.080
foreign rights from Penguin
USA, which is the original

01:04:37.080 --> 01:04:41.350
publisher, and then they can
commission a translation in

01:04:41.350 --> 01:04:43.150
that language for
that country.

01:04:43.150 --> 01:04:45.790
So I actually don't have
much control over that.

01:04:45.790 --> 01:04:48.320
But what I do know is, the more
popular it is in the home

01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:50.230
market where it's launched,
usually, the more interest

01:04:50.230 --> 01:04:52.950
there is in doing translated
versions in other countries.

01:04:52.950 --> 01:04:55.180
So my hope is that
that will happen.

01:04:55.180 --> 01:04:57.920
But I also think it's going to
be a hard book to translate,

01:04:57.920 --> 01:04:59.601
because there's a lot
of humor in it.

01:04:59.601 --> 01:05:01.485
[LAUGHS]

01:05:01.485 --> 01:05:01.960
Yeah.

01:05:01.960 --> 01:05:04.290
Thank you.

01:05:04.290 --> 01:05:04.560
Yes.

01:05:04.560 --> 01:05:04.830
DAGMAR DOLATSCHKO: Yeah.

01:05:04.830 --> 01:05:07.280
Dagmar Dolatschko with Peritus
Language Services.

01:05:07.280 --> 01:05:09.210
Thank you for this
beautiful book.

01:05:09.210 --> 01:05:09.810
This is great.

01:05:09.810 --> 01:05:13.450
We need to get the word out
more about our profession.

01:05:13.450 --> 01:05:15.730
But I have a question
which maybe you can

01:05:15.730 --> 01:05:17.410
answer because of your--

01:05:17.410 --> 01:05:20.580
all your insights with Common
Sense Advisory.

01:05:20.580 --> 01:05:24.770
With this increasing amount of
volume, we're just buried--

01:05:24.770 --> 01:05:25.170
[LAUGHS]

01:05:25.170 --> 01:05:26.440
to use your word--

01:05:26.440 --> 01:05:27.920
in content.

01:05:27.920 --> 01:05:31.090
And the ever-increasing
price pressure.

01:05:31.090 --> 01:05:34.140
Where do you see quality
going in translation?

01:05:34.140 --> 01:05:36.750
And that people still
understand, like in any other

01:05:36.750 --> 01:05:39.670
profession, they will get
what they pay for?

01:05:39.670 --> 01:05:40.470
NATALY KELLY: Yes.

01:05:40.470 --> 01:05:46.690
Well, we did a study in 2008
on quality, and how buyers

01:05:46.690 --> 01:05:47.850
define quality.

01:05:47.850 --> 01:05:49.510
And one of the very interesting
things that we

01:05:49.510 --> 01:05:52.550
found was that quality was
defined slightly differently,

01:05:52.550 --> 01:05:54.760
depending on who was buying.

01:05:54.760 --> 01:05:58.660
And so buyers in the retail
sector, for example, told us,

01:05:58.660 --> 01:06:01.170
it doesn't matter to us if the
product name is spelled wrong,

01:06:01.170 --> 01:06:03.750
or even if the description
has a typo.

01:06:03.750 --> 01:06:07.440
But if the numbers are wrong,
we have a major problem.

01:06:07.440 --> 01:06:09.540
Because if we've advertised that
that product is on sale

01:06:09.540 --> 01:06:13.910
for $199.99, and they get a
decimal point wrong, or they

01:06:13.910 --> 01:06:17.200
get a number wrong, we are
out millions of dollars.

01:06:17.200 --> 01:06:19.320
So for them, the way
they define quality

01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:22.780
was accuracy of numbers.

01:06:22.780 --> 01:06:24.890
So that was in the
retail sector.

01:06:24.890 --> 01:06:29.200
In sectors like life sciences,
of course, every single thing

01:06:29.200 --> 01:06:30.680
has to be perfect.

01:06:30.680 --> 01:06:33.220
There has to be no room for
mistranslations, because human

01:06:33.220 --> 01:06:35.390
lives are on the line.

01:06:35.390 --> 01:06:38.640
And in the automotive sector,
it depends on the type of

01:06:38.640 --> 01:06:39.540
content, of course.

01:06:39.540 --> 01:06:42.750
But for some things, like
user-generated content, of

01:06:42.750 --> 01:06:45.580
course, and certain help
content, it was viewed as

01:06:45.580 --> 01:06:49.140
acceptable to use machine
translation, and to have some

01:06:49.140 --> 01:06:51.770
disclaimer that this is not
perfect translation.

01:06:51.770 --> 01:06:55.220
And that if you need a perfect
translation, contact us.

01:06:55.220 --> 01:06:56.770
And if they'd get a certain
number of inquiries, they

01:06:56.770 --> 01:06:59.630
would start to pay for
professional translation of

01:06:59.630 --> 01:07:01.760
that with a human involved.

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:04.330
But the notion of quality--

01:07:04.330 --> 01:07:07.060
because a lot of times vendors
of translation services will

01:07:07.060 --> 01:07:10.540
talk about quality as if it's
just this one big thing that

01:07:10.540 --> 01:07:11.330
can be defined.

01:07:11.330 --> 01:07:14.280
And our research shows that it's
much more nuanced than

01:07:14.280 --> 01:07:18.050
that, and that there are certain
purposes for which

01:07:18.050 --> 01:07:19.820
different levels of quality
are acceptable.

01:07:19.820 --> 01:07:22.640
And we've actually gone to the
trouble of defining different

01:07:22.640 --> 01:07:24.780
levels of quality for different
content types in

01:07:24.780 --> 01:07:26.390
some of our research.

01:07:26.390 --> 01:07:29.280
So, the answer is, quality
depends on

01:07:29.280 --> 01:07:31.780
who's doing the buying.

01:07:31.780 --> 01:07:32.480
DAGMAR DOLATSCHKO: Thank you.

01:07:32.480 --> 01:07:34.350
NATALY KELLY: Mm-hmm.

01:07:34.350 --> 01:07:36.440
MALE SPEAKER: I'm interested to
follow up on what you said

01:07:36.440 --> 01:07:40.140
about not everybody should be a
translator even if he or she

01:07:40.140 --> 01:07:42.650
speaks multiple languages.

01:07:42.650 --> 01:07:44.340
So, who should be
a translator?

01:07:44.340 --> 01:07:47.930
And what characteristics does
that person need to make that

01:07:47.930 --> 01:07:48.540
successful?

01:07:48.540 --> 01:07:50.436
NATALY KELLY: Mm-hmm.

01:07:50.436 --> 01:07:53.385
Well, the reasons that
translators--

01:07:53.385 --> 01:07:55.770
or would-be professional
translators and interpreters--

01:07:55.770 --> 01:07:59.350
fail exams are different
depending on if we're talking

01:07:59.350 --> 01:08:00.570
about translation
or interpreting.

01:08:00.570 --> 01:08:02.360
But from an interpreting
perspective--

01:08:02.360 --> 01:08:03.310
because that's--

01:08:03.310 --> 01:08:06.170
I have actually graded exams
for interpreting.

01:08:06.170 --> 01:08:09.440
I can say that the reason that
they typically fail is because

01:08:09.440 --> 01:08:11.510
they haven't worked enough
on interpreting skills.

01:08:11.510 --> 01:08:14.050
So, memory length.

01:08:14.050 --> 01:08:17.580
Being able to remember the
information and transfer the

01:08:17.580 --> 01:08:20.770
information without losing
information.

01:08:20.770 --> 01:08:21.870
Or transforming it.

01:08:21.870 --> 01:08:24.350
Because that's another thing
that sometimes interpreters

01:08:24.350 --> 01:08:27.540
will accidentally just change
the meaning or forget

01:08:27.540 --> 01:08:29.540
something, or they mishear
something.

01:08:29.540 --> 01:08:30.760
They don't comprehend
properly.

01:08:30.760 --> 01:08:32.790
And so they say something
different than what was

01:08:32.790 --> 01:08:33.770
actually said.

01:08:33.770 --> 01:08:35.680
So, that's the reason
that people fail a

01:08:35.680 --> 01:08:36.500
lot of those exams.

01:08:36.500 --> 01:08:39.729
A lot of it is lack of
preparation, lack of training,

01:08:39.729 --> 01:08:42.310
and lack of practice,
lack of skills.

01:08:42.310 --> 01:08:46.810
Not everybody has the skills and
has the ability to retain

01:08:46.810 --> 01:08:49.100
large segments of information
and transfer them.

01:08:49.100 --> 01:08:52.250
And some people simply lack
the language proficiency.

01:08:52.250 --> 01:08:57.189
Because you might be fluent
in two languages, but that

01:08:57.189 --> 01:08:59.180
doesn't mean that you can
be, for example, a court

01:08:59.180 --> 01:09:00.319
interpreter.

01:09:00.319 --> 01:09:03.020
If I ask you to say
"arraignment" in another

01:09:03.020 --> 01:09:05.120
language-- even if you speak
that language, you can talk to

01:09:05.120 --> 01:09:06.390
your friends and family--

01:09:06.390 --> 01:09:08.580
you might not know how
to say arraignment

01:09:08.580 --> 01:09:10.100
in that other language.

01:09:10.100 --> 01:09:13.410
So, part of it is lack of
terminology knowledge, and

01:09:13.410 --> 01:09:15.990
specialist terminology
in particular.

01:09:15.990 --> 01:09:17.689
So, that's the reason
that a lot of

01:09:17.689 --> 01:09:19.580
interpreters fail exams.

01:09:19.580 --> 01:09:22.720
In the case of translation,
it's quite similar.

01:09:22.720 --> 01:09:24.819
Sometimes it's making mistakes
with transferring meaning,

01:09:24.819 --> 01:09:26.710
sometimes it's not knowing how
to use the appropriate

01:09:26.710 --> 01:09:29.590
resources to research
terminology, and not knowing

01:09:29.590 --> 01:09:33.050
how to apply tools, or use
tools in the case of some

01:09:33.050 --> 01:09:36.399
exams, depending on who's
doing me the testing.

01:09:36.399 --> 01:09:39.140
So there are a lot of reasons
why translators and

01:09:39.140 --> 01:09:40.100
interpreters will fail.

01:09:40.100 --> 01:09:42.420
But I would say the biggest
reason is because they

01:09:42.420 --> 01:09:46.410
overestimate their level of
ability to manipulate the

01:09:46.410 --> 01:09:50.090
language and to really go deep
in terms of terminology and in

01:09:50.090 --> 01:09:53.180
terms of understanding in
a specialized area.

01:09:53.180 --> 01:09:55.040
MALE SPEAKER: Well,
thank you, Nataly.

01:09:55.040 --> 01:09:55.540
NATALY KELLY: Thank you.

01:09:55.540 --> 01:09:55.840
[APPLAUSE].

01:09:55.840 --> 01:09:56.440
NATALY KELLY: Thank you.

01:09:56.440 --> 01:09:57.690
[APPLAUSE].

